Rough as things still are, the metro area looks to be past the coronavirus peak without completely overwhelming hospitals, as happened so tragically in Italy.
New York not only didn’t run out of ventilators, as feared for so long, it’s sending some to other states.
“We’ve been given clear direction to produce as many as possible,” said Nicholas Melchiaorre, manager at Rutgers’ Clinical Genomics Lab.
We’re past the worst of it, with clear signs that the general public can soon start leaving their apartments again and get back to work.
If it’s not the beginning of the end, it’s at least far, far more than the end of the beginning.